{
  "answer": "**The opening couplet of the ghazal \"Dil-e-naadaan tujhe hua kya hai\" (Chapter 36 of *Diwan-E-Ghalib*) by Mirza Ghalib directly asks what has happened to the \"foolish\" or \"naive\" heart and seeks the remedy for its deep pain.**[^1]\n\n> My foolish heart, what's led you to this sway?  \n> For this deep pain, what is the healing way? Pray, what is it?[^1]\n\nThis couplet personifies the heart (*dil-e-naadaan*, literally \"naive/ignorant heart\") as afflicted by an inexplicable sway or turmoil, questioning the nature of its ailment and cure.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/36-dil-e-naadaan-tujhe-hua-kya-hai/translation/#p-414b38).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [chapter](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/36-dil-e-naadaan-tujhe-hua-kya-hai/translation/).",
